04635nam a22008295i 9780520922785DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20022003cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209227857 a10.1525/97805209227852doi  a(DE-B1597)543188  a(OCoLC)1163878127  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDS707b.S4713 2002eb 7aART0190002bisacsh04a95122202aA Chinese Bestiary :bStrange Creatures from the ‹i›Guideways through Mountains and Seas‹/i› /ced. by Richard E. Strassberg.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2002] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (338 p.) :b1 fronstisp.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA Chinese Bestiary presents a fascinating pageant of mythical creatures from a unique and enduring cosmography written in ancient China. The Guideways through Mountains and Seas, compiled between the fourth and first centuries b.c.e., contains descriptions of hundreds of fantastic denizens of mountains, rivers, islands, and seas, along with minerals, flora, and medicine. The text also represents a wide range of beliefs held by the ancient Chinese. Richard Strassberg brings the Guideways to life for modern readers by weaving together translations from the work itself with information from other texts and recent archaeological finds to create a lavishly illustrated guide to the imaginative world of early China.Unlike the bestiaries of the late medieval period in Europe, the Guideways was not interpreted allegorically; the strange creatures described in it were regarded as actual entities found throughout the landscape. The work was originally used as a sacred geography, as a guidebook for travelers, and as a book of omens. Today, it is regarded as the richest repository of ancient Chinese mythology and shamanistic wisdom. The Guideways may have been illustrated from the start, but the earliest surviving illustrations are woodblock engravings from a rare 1597 edition. Seventy-six of those plates are reproduced here for the first time, and they provide a fine example of the Chinese engraver's art during the late Ming dynasty. This beautiful volume, compiled by a well-known specialist in the field, provides a fascinating window on the thoughts and beliefs of an ancient people, and will delight specialists and general readers alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aFolklorezChina. 0aMythology, Chinese. 7aART / Asian / General.2bisacsh  aancient chinese beliefs.  aancient chinese myths.  aancient chinese.  aancient folklore.  aancient mythology.  aasian folklore.  aasian mythology.  achina guide.  achinese book of omens.  achinese fauna.  achinese flora.  achinese folklore.  achinese geography.  achinese literature.  achinese mountains.  achinese mythology.  achinese shaman.  achinese wisdom.  afolklore.  amedieval china.  amythical creatures.  amythology.  awarring states china.  awestern han dynasty.1 aStrassberg, Richard E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052029851440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092278540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520922785423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520922785/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles